T1  - Strategy and Reality: A Challenge for Business Policy
AU  - Leontiades, Milton
Y1  - 1979/04/01
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1979.4289026
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1979.4289026
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 275
EP  - 279
VL  - 4
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article attempts to establish a deliberate, empirical-based development of the underlying theory for the policy course. The author notes that a course in business policy is now commonly the capstone course in business school curricula, generally built on the concept of strategy formulation by top business managers. These courses typically bring together the theories of marketing, management, accounting, finance, organizational behavior, quantitative methods and economics applied to situational problems. The author suggests that it has become necessary to develop a formal theoretical structure for these courses that recognizes business planning, portfolio management and strategy. He examines several possible instruction methods and discusses their benefits and drawbacks.
AB  - This article attempts to establish a deliberate, empirical-based development of the underlying theory for the policy course. The author notes that a course in business policy is now commonly the capstone course in business school curricula, generally built on the concept of strategy formulation by top business managers. These courses typically bring together the theories of marketing, management, accounting, finance, organizational behavior, quantitative methods and economics applied to situational problems. The author suggests that it has become necessary to develop a formal theoretical structure for these courses that recognizes business planning, portfolio management and strategy. He examines several possible instruction methods and discusses their benefits and drawbacks.
